  <main>
    <article id="articles">
      <h2>How to Study Effectively</h2>
      
      <section>
        <h3>1. Set Clear Goals</h3>
        <p>Before you start studying, define what you want to achieve. Whether it’s mastering a topic or completing an assignment, setting goals helps you stay focused and motivated.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>2. Create a Study Schedule</h3>
        <p>Plan your study sessions in advance. Break down large topics into smaller, manageable chunks and allocate time for each subject to maintain balance.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>3. Use Active Learning Techniques</h3>
        <p>Engage with your study material—summarize what you read, quiz yourself, or explain concepts to someone else. Active learning improves understanding and memory retention.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>4. Take Breaks</h3>
        <p>Use the Pomodoro technique: study for 25 minutes, then take a 5-minute break. Short breaks prevent burnout and keep your brain fresh.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>5. Review Regularly</h3>
        <p>Consistent review helps move information from short-term to long-term memory. Revisit key notes and concepts weekly.</p>
      </section>
    </article>

